    <body>
      <pb n="1R"/>
      <p rend="align(center)">
        <placeName>Richmond</placeName>
        <date>Oct 29<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1829</date>
      </p>
      <p>My dear <addressee>Isaac</addressee></p>
      <p rend="indent(2)">I received your Letter yesterday, when I <sic>send</sic> you the Letter I
        said<lb/> I was Quite <sic>will</sic>, but since I have got the same pains in my hand but
        hope<lb/> to get better of it in a short time. I shall Try to sell my stock of goodsas[?]
        soon<lb/> as possible, but I find great <sic>difficlty</sic> in <sic>colecting</sic> [?] nor
        any body<lb/> has paid as yet best hope to be able to get some of them to pay me, I am<lb/>
        pleased that my old friends and <sic>acquaintence</sic> have not forgotten me<lb/> and am
        much obliged to my friends the <persName>Piexottos</persName> for their kind invitation<lb/>
        I shall <sic>allways</sic> remember those kind offers and shall be happy to return<lb/> the
        same whenever in my power, tell <persName>miss Simha</persName> if she does not come<lb/>
        here soon I shall be obliged to [?] and run away with her, I shall, sure<lb/> take
          <persName>Miss Rachel</persName> and Miss I do not know her name also, I shall send you as
        many papers and can <sic>colect</sic><lb/> if I can send them by <sic>prived</sic>
        conveyance which I expect will be shortly as<lb/>
        <persName>Mr I Philips</persName> is here and he will take them on to you.
          <persName>Cohen</persName> has done wrong<lb/> in <sic>medling</sic> with the Parsons, did
        he want to pray for them a thing Quite<lb/> unusual for a jew to pray for christions[?]
          <sic>supose</sic> a <sic>christion</sic> parson would come<lb/> in our meetings and would
          <del>we</del> let him pray for us no we would not, he was<lb/> advised by <persName>Mr
          Judah</persName>
        <persName>Mr Myers</persName>, and <persName>Marx</persName> not to ask it,
          <persName>Mordecai</persName> also did not<lb/> want him to interfere in the Business, yet
        did he persist in his meddling<lb/> in a thing where he could give nothing, <persName>Mr
          Mordecai</persName> has left Town, he told<lb/> me he would have wrote to you but was busy
        with his affairs Desires<lb/> to be remembered to you, I hope you will get better of that
        old <sic>complain</sic>,<lb/> of yours. I also hope you will be able to have a full school
        in time<lb/> remember me to all my friends particularly to <persName>Mr Mrs
          Piexotto</persName><lb/> and all the Dear girls your Aunt, <persName>Mrs Depass</persName>
        <persName>Rinah</persName>
        <persName>abby</persName> send<lb/>
        <sic>there</sic> Love to you, remember your aunt to <persName>Mr Mrs Piexotto</persName> she wishes<lb/>
        <sic>mightyly</sic> to see her</p>
      <p rend="indent(5)">I remain your friend <persName role="author">Zalma Rehine</persName></p>
      <p>NB <persName>Mrs Grace Marks</persName> is safe arrived in
          <placeName><sic>Cincinatti</sic></placeName> she has the [?]<lb/> of 8 or 9 Boarders,
          <persName>Louisa Block</persName> was <sic>marred</sic> ערב סוכת<lb/> THIS IS A TEST
          <persName>Mr Davis</persName> of <placeName>Petersburg</placeName> told me you
          <sic>marred</sic> his Brother you named <persName>Mr Cohen</persName>
        <lb/> Daughter of <placeName>norfolk</placeName> let me know if it was any benefit to you.
        adieu</p>
      <pb n="2V"/>
      <p>
        <addressee>Mr Isaac Leeser</addressee>
      </p>
      <p>to the care of <persName>Mr A. C Peixotto</persName></p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">
        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
      </p>
    </body>
